-- Australia, N.Z. Stocks: Ramelius, Rio, Nufarm, Stockland
-- B y   D a v i d   F i c k l i n g
-- 2012-03-27T01:59:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-03-26/australia-n-z-stocks-beach-rio-nufarm-oz-stockland.html
Australia ’s  S&P/ASX 200 (AS51)  index rose
0.8 percent to 4,297.80 at 12:41 p.m. in Sydney. New Zealand’s
 NZX 50 Index (NZSE50FG)  climbed 0.3 percent to 3,481.70 in Wellington. The
following were some of the most active stocks on the market:  Gold mining stocks: Spot gold hit $1,693.60 in overnight
trade, its highest level in two months.  Ramelius Resources Ltd. (RMS)  , focused on gold projects
in Western Australia, had the biggest gain in Australia’s
benchmark index, climbing 9.7 percent to 84.5 Australian cents.
In Wellington,  OceanaGold Ltd. (OGC)   gained 2.2 percent to
NZ$3.21, the third-largest increase on New Zealand’s benchmark
gauge.  The  S&P/ASX 200 (AS51) ’s information technology sub-index was the
best-performing  sector  of the market, with a 2.3 percent
increase, followed by the health index, which climbed 1.2
percent.  Telstra Corp. (TLS)  , the country’s largest phone
company, rose 0.5 percent to A$3.235, while  SMS Management &
Technology Ltd. (SMX) , a Melbourne-based information technology
services group, rose 3.9 percent to A$5.83.  Nufarm Ltd. (NUF)  (NUF AU), Australia’s No. 1 herbicides and
pesticides manufacturer, fell 3.3 percent to A$4.93. The company
released first-half sales figures that were 8.3 percent below
analyst expectations.  Stockland (SGP)  , the country’s third-largest listed
property trust, dropped 3.2 percent drop to A$3.04. The company
said that wet weather and the weakness in the country’s housing
market meant that earnings per share during the year would be
3.5 percent below previous forecasts.  Mining stocks: The London Metal Exchange Index of prices
for six industrial commodities including copper and aluminum
rose at the fastest rate in nearly two weeks, climbing 1.3
percent yesterday. Three-month copper futures gained 1.9 percent
to $8,535 per metric ton, the biggest climb since March 9.  Sundance Resources Ltd. (SDL)  (SDL AU), which is developing an
iron-ore mine in central  Africa , rose 5.4 percent to 44.25
Australian cents while  Boart Longyear Ltd. (BLY)  , which
supplies drilling equipment for mine exploration, climbed 5.9
percent to A$4.34.  Rio Tinto Ltd. (RIO)   rose 0.5 percent to A$64.07 after
the world’s third-largest miner said it had completed a $7
billion share buy-back in the company’s London listing.  Mirabela Nickel Ltd. (MBN)  , developing a mine in  Brazil ,
suffered the biggest fall on the benchmark with a 6.9 percent
drop to 74.5 Australian cents. The stock has fallen 33 percent
this year.  Dart Energy Ltd. (DTE)  , which is developing coal seam
gas projects worldwide, fell 3.3 percent to 29.5 Australian
cents. Nymex natural gas fell yesterday to its lowest close in
at least 10 years, closing at A$2.21 per British thermal unit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
